\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 ## 2026-03-14 | npm permissions and user-space isolation\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 \'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 **What happened**: `npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code` failed with EACCES permission denied. macOS npm defaults to `/usr/local/lib/node_modules/`, which is owned by root. The quick fix is `sudo npm install -g`, but that gives every npm package root-level access to the system.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 \'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 **What I learned**: The proper fix is redirecting npm's global directory to a user-owned location (`~/.npm-global`). This is the user-space isolation pattern \'97 install tools in a directory you control rather than a system-wide directory requiring elevated privileges. The same pattern appears in Python virtual environments, Docker non-root containers, Lambda scoped IAM roles, and Kubernetes service accounts. Never elevate permissions when you can scope them down.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 \'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 **Design principle**: Least privilege / user-space isolation \'97 every component gets only the access it needs. If a compromised npm package runs a post-install script, it can only affect your user space, not the entire system. This is defense in depth applied to development tooling.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 \'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 **Interview version**: "Even my local development setup follows least-privilege principles. Rather than using sudo for npm global installs, I configured a user-scoped directory. It's the same pattern as running Docker containers as non-root users or assigning Lambda functions scoped IAM roles \'97 never give more access than necessary, even in development."\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
